Investigating Biomarkers Associated with Cytomegalovirus Short Term Post Heart Transplant

End of Co-op Assignment

Author

Rithika Nair, Linda Lapp

Published

August 1, 2024

1 Introduction

Heart transplant surgery is a life-saving treatment for patients with heart failure. In heart transplant surgery, one of the major negative outcomes is acute rejection. To prevent and treat rejections, patients are administered with maximal tolerable doses of immunosuppressive drugs. However, excessive immunosuppression can cause severe complications, such as infections like the reactivation of cytomegalovirus (CMV). CMV is a herpes virus that is commonly found in the adult human population. It presents as asymptomatic or mild flu-like symptoms in healthy adults but can have serious implications, such as pneumonia and gastrointestinal diseases in immunocompromised patients. It can reactivate in about 20% of transplant patients [1] and is influenced by numerous factors such as the transplanted organ, the immune system of the transplant recipient, the immunosuppression drug levels [2]. Much of the existing literature focuses on the the detection of CMV antibodies in the donor and recipient to predict CMV post-transplant. There is limited research investigating other factors that contribute to reactivation of CMV post-transplant. Our goal is to assess how a common immunosuppressant tacrolimus and molecular biomarkers are associated with the treatment of CMV, short-term post-transplant. This study aims to assess how tacrolimus, a common immunosuppressant, and molecular biomarker are associated with the treatment of CMV, short-term post-transplant.

2 Methods

2.1 Data source and sample selection

The Biomarkers in Transplantation (BiT) program is a prospective, observational study conducted across multiple transplantation sites in Canada. Adult heart-transplant patients present in the outpatient, pretransplant clinic during a routine visit or in inpatient cardiac units before the transplant surgery were enrolled. Recipients with multiple or different solid organ transplants, were HIV positive or received orgain from HIV-positive donors were excluded [3]. This study uses the data collected from recipients enrolled in the BiT program from 2018 to 2020 at St.Â Paulâs Hospital in Vancouver, BC.

Blood samples were obtained from these patients at 0.5, 1, 1.5, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 12 and 24 weeks post-transplantation and then every 6 months until the third year post-transplant. Clinical and laboratory data was also collected from these patients at different time points [3]. For this study, samples and data collected between 0 to 180 days post-transplant are included. The samples are then time matched the clinical and laboratory data such that for each sample, clinical and laboratory data is recorded within 1 day of each other.

Transcriptomic profiling was performed on the blood samples using two assays: TGS assay and HEARTBiT assay. The TGS assay is 36-gene biomarker panel that measures the gene expression for 9 T conventional-marker and 24 T regulatory-marker genes and 3 housekeeping genes. The HEARTBiT assay is a blood-based profiling assay that computes a score which is then used to identify heart transplant patients at risk for ACR. This 12-gene panel measures the gene expression for 3 housekeeping genes and 9 genes used to compute the HEARTBiT score.[4]

2.2 Data processing and statistical analyses

2.2.1 Linear Regression Analysis

All analyses were conducted in the R environment. To understand the association between tacrolimus and CMV treatment, we initially assessed two relationships: one between tacrolimus dosing and CMV treatment and another between tacrolimus concentration and CMV treatment. Both of these analyses were performed using a linear model while adjusting for age, sex and time post-transplant. The significance level was set to 5%.

The association between tacrolimus and CMV treatment is further assessed under two different conditions. In the first condition, we account for the patientsâ overall rejection status indicating the severity of the patientâs rejection post-transplant, if any. This is determined by looking at the histopathologic results, following the ISHLT guidelines (0R = no rejection, 1R = mild rejection, â¥ 2R = moderate to severe rejection), of all the samples from a patient. If a patient has at least one 2R graded sample, they are classified as moderate rejectors. If a patient has at least one 1R graded sample and no 2R sample, they are classified as mild rejectors. If a patient only has 0R graded samples and no 2R or 1R sample, they are classified as never rejecting. The relationships between tacrolimus concentration and CMV treatment and between tacrolimus dosing and CMV treatment are assessed within each of these groups using a linear model while adjusting for age, sex and time post-transplant at a 5% significance level.

In the second condition, we account for the patientsâ renal dysfunction period if the patient had a renal dysfunction at any point pre or post-transplant. This is determined by looking at the patientsâ pre-transplant comorbidities recorded in the clinical data and the estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) results recorded post-transplant. The eGFR test is used to determine the level of kidney function such that the patient has normal renal function if eGFR result â¥ 90 mL/min and renal dysfunction if eGFR result < 90 mL/min. If a patient has renal dysfunction both pre- and post-transplant, then they are classified into the âAlwaysâ group. If a patient has renal dysfunction only pre-transplant, then they are classified into the âPre-TX but managedâ group. If a patient has renal dysfunction only post-transplant, then they are classified into the âNewâ group. If a patient does not have renal dysfunction neither pre- nor post-transplant, then they are classified into the âNeverâ group. The relationships between tacrolimus concentration and CMV treatment and between tacrolimus dosing and CMV treatment are assessed within each of these groups using a linear model while adjusting for age, sex and time post-transplant at a 5% significance level.

2.2.2 Differential Gene Expression Analysis

To understand molecular biomarker associated with CMV treatment, gene expression is compared between samples from patients who received CMV treatment (i.e., treated samples) and samples from patients who did not received CMV treatment (i.e., untreated samples).

Raw transcript counts from the TGS and HEARTBiT assays were normalized sequentially. First, the samples were normalized to the geometric mean of 6 internal positive control probes. The resulting counts were then normalized to geometric mean nean of the housekeeping genes (RPL23A, HNRPA1, and UFC1 for TGS assay, ACTB for HEARTBiT assay) across all samples [[4]][5].

The normalized gene expression data is divided into two subsets. The first subset consisted of data from treated samples collected prior to the first CMV treatment and data from all untreated samples. The second subset consisted of data from treated samples collected during CMV treatment and data from all untreated samples. Differential gene expression analysis is performed on the normalized gene expression data from the two assays, using the linear models for microarray data (limma) package in R. The false discovery rate is set to 10%.

3 Results

We analyzed 298 blood samples from 40 patients (27 male and 13 female, median age = 60.0 years, IQR = 12.0 years) within the first 180 days post-transplant. Out the 40 patients, 14 were treated for CMV (7 male and 7 female, median age = 59.9 years, IQR = 9.0 years) and 26 were not treated for CMV (20 male and 6 female, median age = 55.5 years, IQR = 12.0 years). Demographics and clinical data summary for patients and samples can be found in TableÂ 1 and TableÂ 2 respectively.

3.1 Association between Tacrolimus Dose and CMV Treatment

In our initial analysis between tacrolimus dosing and CMV treatment, there is no significant association between the two variables when adjusting for age, sex and time since transplant (p = 0.083) as shown in TableÂ 3 and FigureÂ 1 (a).

Several factors such as renal function and ACR status may influence the tacrolimus dosing for each patient. Hence, we further assessed the association between tacrolimus dosing and CMV treatment while accounting for the patientsâ renal dysfunction period and the overall ACR status. In the overall ACR status condition, there is a significant difference between dosing and CMV (p = 0.016) in moderate rejectors. This indicates that in patients who have at least one 2R sample post-tranplant, those who are treated for CMV tend to have a lower dose than those who are not treated for CMV, as shown below in TableÂ 4. No significant difference is observed in any other groups (FigureÂ 1 (b)).

In the renal dysfunction period condition, there is a significant difference between dosing and CMV (p < 0.001) in the New group. This indicates that in patients who develop a renal dysfunction only after the transplantation surgery, those who are treated for CMV tend to have a lower dose than those who are not treated for CMV, as shown below in TableÂ 5. No siginificant difference is observed in any other groups (FigureÂ 1 (c)).

3.2 Association between Tacrolimus Concentration and CMV Treatment

In our initial analysis between tacrolimus concentration and CMV treatment, there is no significant association between the two variables when adjusting for age, sex and time since transplant (p = 0.244) as shown in TableÂ 6 and FigureÂ 2 (a) and FigureÂ 2 (b).

Similar to dosing, factors such as renal function and ACR status may influence the tacrolimus concentration for each patient. Hence, we further assessed the association between tacrolimus concentration and CMV treatment while accounting for the patientsâ renal dysfunction period and the overall ACR status. In the overall ACR status condition, there is a significant difference between concentration and CMV (p < 0.001) in never rejecting. This indicates that in patients who have never had a 1R or 2R samples, those who are treated for CMV tend to have a slight higher dose than those who are not treated for CMV, as shown below in TableÂ 7. However, this could be a spurious correlation since the never rejecting group has insufficient number of samples to accurate infer a correlation. No significant difference is observed in any other groups (FigureÂ 2 (c)).

In the renal dysfunction period condition, no significant difference is observed between concentration and CMV in any of the groups. This indicates that renal dysfunction does not affect the tacrolimus concentration levels in the blood between patients who were treated and not treated for CMV, as shown below in TableÂ 8 and FigureÂ 2 (d).

3.3 Differential Gene Expression Analysis

We analyzed blood samples from the same 40 patients. 187 samples from these 40 patients were run on the TGS assay and the demographic and clinical data summary can be found in TableÂ 10. 395 samples from these 40 patients were run on the HEARTBiT assay and the demographic and clinical data summary can be found in TableÂ 11.

3.3.1 TGS Assay

Through gene expression analysis, we found that in patients who received CMV treatment, four genes higher expressed in T-conventional cells (ANK3, DACT1, HDGFRP3, LPIN2) and one gene higher expressed in T-regulatory cells (FOXP3) are significantly upregulated, and two genes higher expressed in T-regulatory cells (TNFRSF9, ZNK532) are significantly downregulated before the CMV treatment (TableÂ 12 (a), FigureÂ 3 (a)). In patients who received CMV treatment, two genes higher expressed in T-conventional cells (ANK3, HDGFRP3) are significantly upregulated and five genes higher expressed in T-regulatory cells (CSF2RB, IL1R1, IL1R2, TNFRSF9, ZNK532) are significantly downregulated during the CMV treatment (TableÂ 12 (b), FigureÂ 3 (b)).

3.3.2 HEARTBiT Assay

Through gene expression analysis, we found that in patients who received CMV treatment, four genes from the assay (CTSE, HEBP1, IFIT2, VNN1) are significantly upregulated before the CMV treatment (TableÂ 13 (a), FigureÂ 4 (a)) and one gene (HEBP1) is significantly upregulated during the CMV treatment (TableÂ 13 (a), FigureÂ 4 (b)).

4 Discussion

Tacrolimus is administered and monitored to ensure that the patient achieves a target concentration level to avoid toxicity and the negative outcomes resulting from the toxicity. This toxicity is affected by several factors including the metabolism rate, drug-drug interactions [6] and the importance of considering these factors is further highlighted by this study. Our study indicates that tacrolimus dosing may help identify patients at risk for CMV provided that we consider factors such as ACR status and renal function. The same however, cannot be said for tacrolimus whole blood concentration. Existing literature discusses the inefficiency of whole blood tacrolimus concentration in preventing toxicity [6] and our study is in accordance with this because regardless of whether confounding factors are considered or not, tacrolimus concentration does not provide insights to identify patients at risk for CMV.

In the earlier stages of the BiT research program, a study demonstrated that the TGS and HEARTBiT assays were useful tools in identifying patients at risk for acute cellular rejection post-transplant [[4]][7]. Hence, we investigate if the same assays can be used to identify at-risk patients for CMV. Our study demonstrated genes from the TGS assay higher expressed in both T-conv and T-reg cells and certain genes from the HEARTBiT assay are differentially expressed between patients with CMV and without CMV. In patients with CMV, fewer genes were differentially expressed during CMV treatment than before the treatment. Identifying the roles of these genes with regards to CMV could help narrow down the exact gene biomarkers that indicate the onset of CMV and its the progression over time.

One of the major limitations of this study is the small sample size. This is a common challenge in the research of heart transplantation due to the rarity of the heart transplantation cases. In British Columbia, between 2018 and 2020, there was an average of 30 heart transplant cases per year and the St.Â Paulâs Hospital is the only adult heart transplant center in the province [8]. Hence, limited data is available for us to investigate outcomes related to heart transplant. Although we analyze data from blood samples collected at specific time points, not every sample has clinical or laboratory data associated with it since post-transplant follow up care may be done in other medical facilities than our primary site or due to irregular collection of CMV related data. We attempt to overcome this limitation by adjusting for time in all of our analyses however, this limitation may still have impacted our ability to identify significant association between tacrolimus and CMV at a patient-level. This identifies the need for regular monitoring of CMV associated clinical and laboratory data to better understand the onset of CMV in patients post-transplant.

Our primary site, St.Â Paulâs Hospital, is one of 8 transplant centres in Canada and using patient data from this site is a strength of this study. Since this site has one of the highest number of heart transplant surgeries in the country [9], these findings could apply to the entire Canadian population, and not just those in British Columbia. However, external validation using data from other centres is required. To our knowledge, this is the first study to examine gene expression as a biomarker for CMV short term post transplant. This is another strength of our study as it provides a novel contribution to better diagnostic tools for clinicians to identify patients at risk for CMV.

Future work involves the validation of the TGS assay with more samples and further exploration of differentially expression genes to thoroughly understand their role in identifying patients at risk for CMV. Additionally, we aim to use the significantly associated clinical factors along with the findings from the TGS and HEARTBiT assays to build a predictive model that can be provides the chances of patient developing CMV based on personalized, patient-specific factors.

5 Conclusion

This study describes the association between CMV and tacrolimus by investigating the relationships between CMV treatment and tacrolimus dosing and CMV treatment and tacrolimus concentration. It also included potential confounding factors such as the patientâs acute cellular rejection status and renal function status. There is no significant association between concentration and CMV however, a significant association is found between dosing and CMV when other factors are accounted for. This study demonstrates the importance of including these factors (e.g.Â comorbidities) to understand the effect of tacrolimus on the reactivation of CMV. Genes expressed in T-cells and the HEARTBiT transcriptomic signature could potentially be used to identify patients that are at risk for CMV within 180 days post-transplant. Further analyses and validation with larger sample sizes are required to better understand these biomarkers. This work will lead to a novel clinical decision support tool to determine personalized care practices in heart transplantation, specifically guiding clinicians to titrate the appropriate dose of immunosuppressive drugs to avoid CMV post-transplant.
